#MCMAA simplifies payment process by automatically deducting required monthly payments like Social Security and Medicare.

text: @allycakes73 https://t.co/2uRsf9JNkE
@susanroar https://t.co/2uRsf9JNkE
These issues are too important for political gamesmanship. We need serious leaders who will put our country ahead of politics.
If someone is standing in the way of progress, hold them accountable.
Voters should absolutely hold us accountable for what we're doing, or not doing, to address gun violence.
And the failure to do so makes Congress complicit in the deaths of hundreds of thousands of Americans. I mean, let's be honest here.
Congress is the only institution with the power to actually do something about this violence.
They are weapons of war. They have no place in our communities. And it shouldn't be easier to buy an AR-15 than it is to buy cold medicine.
Their only purpose is to kill as many people as possible, as quickly as possible.
I believe in the Second Amendment and the right to defend yourself and your family. But assault weapons serve no legitimate purpose.
It is infuriating that leaders in Congress have still done nothing to address how easy it is for a lone wolf terrorist to buy a gun.
This is also a reminder that homegrown attacks a threat to our safety. We've seen that at Ft Hood, in Charleston, and now in Orlando.
Demonizing LGBT Americans only exacerbates hatred and intolerance. LGBT people aren't political wedge issues. We are human beings.
LGBT Americans are still targets. Last week, politicians in Washington mocked transgender individuals at a "faith and freedom" conference.
There is too much hatred in this country. You can't look at the TV today and conclude that we have full LGBT equality. We don't.
But mostly about what could possess someone to do something like this. I don't understand it and I don't think I ever will.
I've spent much of today thinking about Orlando. About the victims, their families, and their loved ones.
This is going to be a longer series of Tweets, so please bear with me for a few minutes.

text: .@SpeakerRyan, @BobGoodlatte, take this opportunity to reflect the American people's commitment to full equality for all Americans.

56% of lesbian, gay, and bisexual individuals have experienced discrimination while trying to get health care.
60% of LGBT Americans experience discrimination in their lives. More than 50% of LGBT middle and high schoolers don’t feel safe at school.
Moving forward on the #EqualityAct would have a real impact for millions of Americans.
.@SpeakerRyan pledged to return the House to regular order. Holding an #EqualityAct hearing in @HouseJudiciary would reaffirm that promise.
